## Part 1 — The Wealth Tracker

> ### PROMPT 1 — copy everything in this block into Claude
>
> I want you to build a single-file, local family net-worth tracker as one `tracker.html` file. Requirements:
>
> **Tech:** Plain HTML/CSS/JS in one file. Use Chart.js v4 from a CDN for charts. Persist data in the browser's `localStorage`. No build step, no frameworks, no servers. It must work by double-clicking the file.
>
> **Data model:** A JS object with a `months` array. Each month has:
> - `id` (`"YYYY-MM"`), `label` (e.g. `"Jan 2025"`), `notes`
> - `property`: `{ value, loan }` (equity is derived = value − loan)
> - `stocks`: an object of named holdings, e.g. `{ holdingA: 0, holdingB: 0 }` — ask me for my actual holdings
> - `crypto`: an object of named tokens, e.g. `{ cash: 0, btc: 0, eth: 0 }`
> - `savings`: an object of named accounts, e.g. `{ everyday: 0, savings: 0 }`
> - `otherAssets`: an object, e.g. `{ vehicle: 0 }`
> - `super`: retirement per person, e.g. `{ personA: 0, personB: 0 }`
> - `businessRevenue`: a number or null (skip if not relevant to me)
>
> Net worth for a month = property equity + sum(stocks) + sum(crypto) + sum(savings) + sum(otherAssets) + sum(super). **Important: count property once — equity only, never the gross value on top of equity.**
>
> **Tabs:** Dashboard | Goals | Add Month | History | Settings.
>
> **Dashboard:** a hero "Total Net Worth" number for the latest month, with month-on-month, year-on-year, and financial-year-to-date deltas. KPI cards for property equity, liquid+investments, and super. Three charts: (1) net worth over time, (2) asset allocation donut for the latest month, (3) the loan/mortgage balance over time. Then a goal-progress section.
>
> **Add Month:** a form, pre-filled from the most recent month, so I only tweak what changed. Saving adds or updates that month.
>
> **History:** a table of every month with the category totals and net worth; clicking a row loads it into the form for editing.
>
> **Settings:** Export to a `data.json` file (download), Import from a `data.json` file, Reset to seed, and an editable household display name.
>
> **Charts must use a real time axis** (space points by actual date), so gaps in tracking show as gaps, not as evenly-spaced points that distort the story.
>
> **Aesthetic:** calm and considered, like a private-bank statement, not a busy budgeting app. Warm off-white background, a serif for big numbers, generous spacing, tabular figures for all money. One restrained accent colour.
>
> Before you write code, ask me: my household name, my actual stock holdings, crypto tokens, savings account names, other assets, and how many people's super to track. Then build it and seed it with one example month so it renders.

**After PROMPT 1:** open `tracker.html`, go to **Add Month**, and enter your most recent month for real. Then **Settings → Export** to save your first `data.json` backup.

