## Part 3 — Cashflow from Bank Statements

This is the part that turns the tracker from a scoreboard into a decision tool. You feed Claude your bank statement CSVs; it categorises spending, strips out internal transfers, and tracks your savings rate.

> ### PROMPT 3a — set up the cashflow tab
>
> Add a **Cashflow** tab to the tracker. It reads a `cashflow` object on the data: `{ targetSavingsRate: <number>, months: [...] }`. Each cashflow month has:
> - `id`, `label`
> - `income`: `{ <subcategory>: amount, ... }` (positive numbers)
> - `essentials`, `lifestyle`, `family`: same shape (spending, stored positive)
> - `investment`: capital deployed (e.g. money moved into investments / a business) — tracked separately from spending
> - `uncategorised`: a single number for the long tail
> - `totals`: `{ income, expenses, net, investment_out, savings_rate_pct }`
>
> The tab should show: a hero **savings rate** for the latest month vs my target (green if at/above, amber/red if below); a bar chart of income vs expenses across months; a category-breakdown donut for the latest month; and a table of subcategories with month-on-month change. Set my target savings rate to **<YOUR NUMBER, e.g. 20>%**.

> ### PROMPT 3b — categorise my statements
>
> I'll put my bank statement CSV exports in a `statements/` folder, one file per account (e.g. `accountname_jan-mar.csv`). Read all of them and produce monthly cashflow data in the schema above. Rules:
>
> 1. **Normalise formats.** Different banks export different columns (some have a single signed Amount; others split Credit/Debit). Detect and handle each.
> 2. **Strip internal transfers.** Money moving between *my own* accounts is neither income nor expense — net it out. Look for "transfer", matching debit/credit pairs, and transfers between accounts I tell you are mine.
> 3. **Separate capital from spending.** Money I deploy into investments or a business is `investment`, not an expense — don't let it tank my "spending" figure.
> 4. **Categorise the rest** by merchant/description patterns into income / essentials / lifestyle / family. Use sensible buckets (groceries, utilities, transport, dining out, subscriptions, shopping, healthcare, etc.).
> 5. **Flag what you can't categorise** — show me a grouped list of unknown merchants by total value, and ask me about the big ones. I'll tell you what they are; you learn the mapping.
> 6. **Keep the categorisation rules in a reusable script** so re-running next month is fast.
>
> Then write the monthly aggregates into my `data.json` under `cashflow`, and give me a short report: income, expenses, net, and savings rate per month, plus a 4-month (or however many) summary.
>
> Before you start, ask me: which accounts are mine (to identify internal transfers), where my income lands, and whether to include or exclude any business accounts.

**Monthly habit:** each month, drop the new CSVs in `statements/`, tell Claude "new statements are in," and it re-runs the categoriser. Re-import the updated `data.json` into the tracker. ~5 minutes.

