## Part 4 — The Annual Life-Plan PDF (optional, but the best part)

A one-to-two page designed document you print and hang up each year. Not a balance sheet — a story. Where you came from, where you are, where you're going.

> ### PROMPT 4
>
> Build a separate `life-plan.html` that I open in a browser and print to PDF (Cmd/Ctrl+P → Save as PDF → A4). It should be designed to feel like a keepsake, not a corporate report: a serif display face, warm paper colour, generous margins, restrained gold/ink accents, page breaks between sections. Sections:
>
> 1. **Cover** — family name, "Life Plan · [year]", a short motto.
> 2. **Where we stand** — a snapshot of current net worth and a household roster (names, ages, pets).
> 3. **Our story so far** — a few paragraphs of narrative. Interview me for this; write a first draft in my voice that I can edit.
> 4. **The year ahead** — my active goals as an ordered list of priorities, each with a sentence on why.
> 5. **The horizon** — a 3–5 year vision in a few short tiles.
> 6. **Why we hang this up** — a short, honest closing reflection. This one's personal; ask me what I want my kids/future self to take from it.
> 7. **(Optional) appendix** — a small table of net worth at a few past points, read plainly.
>
> Pull the numbers from my `data.json`. Use real figures, honestly — modest growth told straight beats inflated vanity numbers. Ask me for the narrative bits before writing them.

